postcontent: ** PRICE is BEST OFFER, will entertain all offers as long as its not completely low balling me. Looking to move quickly, contact info at the bottomHello,i am looking to sell my brand new, never fired CZ 805 Bren 11” pistol rifle. Chambered in 5.56×45 and using the ubiquitous STANAG magazine from the AR15/M16, it easily accepts optics and lights on its top and bottom Picatinny rails. Two-port muzzle brake helps keep the pistol solidly on target and reduces recoil and muzzle flip. I have another SBR CZ 805 Bren and I love it. It’s close to the top of the smoothest pistol AR’s that I own, along side my Scar L and KAC SBR.  It retails for $1,800.00, but I paid $1,650.00 when I purchased it. Cold hammer forged, muzzle threaded 1/2x28. The weight is 6.7 lbs and overall Length is 22.75 in.The S1 uses a short-stroke gas piston operating system. “Short-stroke” means the gas piston moves a distance shorter than the length of the cartridge. The stainless steel gas tube and gas block are mounted above the barrel and use a two-position regulator with settings for regular use and a wide-open port for extreme conditions. The S1 uses a reciprocating charging handle that can be mounted on either side of the receiver and also serves as a forward assist when encountering a partially chambered round. The magazine release buttons are ambidextrous, and a plastic shell deflector is mounted at the rear of the ejection port to protect the faces of left-handed shooters (which really helped me since I am left handed). The trigger has a very smooth travel of about 0.5 inches and a pull weight of 5.63 pounds according to my Lyman digital trigger pull gauge.As CZ puts it, the S1 has proven a popular short-barreled-rifle (SBR) candidate for customers wanting to convert it to an NFA firearm. I agree fully. Because of its size, weight and caliber, the S1, wearing a folding stock and other 922r parts, would be slick. ** Also to add, I have a brand new 922r kit for sale along with it if anyone is interested in making it an SBR in the future. title: For Sale:  Rare Browning Superposed 20 ga
postcontent: The post war Belgian Browning Superposed O/U was introduced in 1948 in 12 Ga as the "lightning" model. In 1949 Browning introduced the 20 Guage version, the "Blue Streak" and only made 268 of them that first year (all in Grade I). THIS ONE was made in 1952, one of the 4,153 20 Guage Superposed made that year (from "The Browning Superposed, John M. Browning's Last Legacy" by Ned Schwing). They were offered in any choke configuration and with a solid rib for $219 and an additional $25 would get the ventilated rib option retailing at $244. This example not only features the low serial number but the scarce and desirable ventilated rib as well. The chokes are both Modified. Single trigger and taking 2 3/4" shells with a 26.5" barrel. The buttplate has been replaced with a Pachmyr recoil absorbing pad. The length of pull is 13.5", indicating a good fit for someone built fairly low to the ground. Nice, classic, rare, Belgium-made, John Moses Browning designed firearm.

postcontent: No rebuild or import marks. The old war horse is as expected in rather rough shape. But one has to ask how should it look after being used in two world wars and multiple minor American wars over the course of 70 years. The finish is pretty much worn off with discoloration, numerous dings, and some pitting. It has also likely been cold blued at some point by a previous owner. That said, it appears to retain its original parts. The bore has strong rifling with frosting in the grooves. The grip safety, hammer, and thumb safety have pitting that is likely attributed to use in salt water or a highly corrosive environment.

title: For Sale:  AR15 Heavy Buffer
postcontent: This Heavy buffer, also known as an H or H1 buffer, is approximately 0.8 oz heavier than the standard carbine buffer. This extra weight helps to smooth the function of the AR15 by slightly delaying the unlocking of the action allowing pressure in the chamber to decrease, resulting in easier, more consistent and reliable case extraction. The extra weight also causes the bolt to move forward with more authority, stripping and feeding the next round from the magazine into the chamber more reliably.
